<DOC><DOCNO> AP890224-0231 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0200EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-24 0864</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0904</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two major banks said they were raising theirprime rate half a percentage point to 11.5 percent, the secondincrease in two weeks, lifting the benchmark interest rate to itshighest level since November 1984.   Chase Manhattan Corp. announced first Thursday and was quicklyfollowed by Republic National Bank of New York. Economists said theyexpected other major banks to follow suit Friday.   The increases are effective Friday. The prime rate is a benchmarkfor a wide range of business and consumer loan rates, including carloans and adjustable-rate home mortgages.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Orders to factories for ``big ticket'' durablegoods dropped 3 percent in January, the government said in a reportthat some analysts said could portend a welcome slowdown in economicgrowth.   The Commerce Department said Thursday that total orders fell $4billion to a seasonally adjusted $128.06 billion last month, pulleddown by sharp declines in the volatile transportation and defensesectors.   Virtually all other major industrial categories were down as well.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan,saying a separately regulated thrift industry may not be needed inthe future, told Congress that the Fed will make it easier for bankholding companies to buy troubled savings and loans.   Greenspan also said Thursday that the central bank and theTreasury Department have arranged to support the Federal Home LoanBank system in the event of runs on Sandamp;Ls.   The Fed chairman's comments came as opposition to PresidentBush's Sandamp;L proposal grew among members of Congress fighting topreserve a separate Sandamp;L industry.</TEXT><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Farley Inc. won a four-month battle for WestPoint-Pepperell Inc. as the textile giant accepted a sweetened $3billion buyout offer from the Chicago-based conglomerate.   Pepperell and Farley said Thursday that Farley would pay $58 ashare in cash for Pepperell's outstanding stock and refinancePepperell's debt. The entire transaction would cost Farley $3billion.   Farley will contribute about $300 million in equity, with theremainder being financed by $1.6 billion in high-risk, high-yield``junk'' bonds and $1.2 billion in bank loans.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chrysler Corp. said it plans to replace an agingDetroit assembly plant with a new $1 billion factory that will makea new sport-utility vehicle beginning in 1992, betting that demandfor such vehicles will continue growing into the next decade.   The vehicle, code-named the ``ZJ,'' will be available from Jeepand Dodge dealers and will be the first sport-utility vehiclecarrying the Dodge nameplate, Chrysler said Thursday.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mid-February sales of U.S.-based companies' carsand light trucks rose 1.7 percent from year-earlier levels as theeffects of sales incentives available in early 1988 began to wearoff, the automakers reported.   The eight automakers said Thursday that they sold cars and lighttrucks at an average daily rate of 36,769 during the Feb. 11-20period this year, compared with a daily rate of 35,158 during thesame time last year.   The overall sales rate during the period was bolstered by a 5.4percent increase in truck sales, which offset a 0.3 percent declinein car sales.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Labor leaders staged a rowdy show of support forMachinists planning to strike Eastern Airlines, receiving a boostfrom the airline's pilots while predicting President Bush wouldintervene to stop a walkout.   The AFL-CIO Executive Council joined members of the Machinistsand other unions at the rally Thursday at Eastern's headquarters.   The labor leaders predicted they would mount a unified front andstall air travel and cargo if the 8,500 machinists and groundpersonnel strike Eastern as planned March 4.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sears, Roebuck and Co. announced it is ready toimplement the cornerstone of its restructuring plans with a rollbackof prices on more than 1.5 billion pieces of merchandise.   The nation's largest retailer said Thursday it would close its825 Sears stores for 42 hours next week _ from 6 p.m. Monday untilnoon Wednesday _ to change the prices marked on clothes, hardware,appliances, furniture and other items to conform with its new``everyday low price'' strategy.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Those soulful, animated dancing raisins have beentaking their bows for the California raisin industry for about 2{years, but television viewers apparently still love them.   The California raisin commercials led Video Storyboard TestsInc.'s annual list of most popular ad campaigns in 1988 for thesecond consecutive year.   The campaigns for Pepsi and Diet Pepsi, including a four-part adstarring singer Michael Jackson and an ad with actor Michael J. Foxtrying to avoid a watchdog blocking the way to the soda machine,placed second.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The stock market eked out a small gain Thursday, steadying afterWednesday's sharp drop. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrialsgained 5.53 points at 2,289.46.   The dollar slipped lower as pessimism about the U.S. budget andtrade deficits weighed on the foreign-exchange markets. Gold pricesrose.   Bond prices fell and short-term interest rates jumped.   Renewed fears of inflation gave gold futures prices another lift.Grain, livestock and energy futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>